  "prompt": "Is the scheme of money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. The term \"money laundering\" originates from the practice of making \"dirty\" money appear \"clean.\"\n\nMost jurisdictions have stringent laws and regulations aimed at preventing money laundering. These laws typically require financial institutions to monitor and report suspicious transactions to the authorities. In many countries, money laundering is considered a serious felony, and those convicted of it can face severe penalties, including hefty fines and lengthy prison sentences.\n\nFor example, in the United States, money laundering is prohibited under the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986. Similar laws exist in other countries, often in line with international standards set by organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).\n\nIf you have more specific questions or need detailed information, feel free to ask!",
